<section xml:id="sec_seventh-intro" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Moment of Inertia</title>
  
   <introduction>
    <p>
      Moment of inertia is a property of a material during rotation. 
      It is a measure of sluggishness (resistance to any changes) in object's 
      rotational motion. Moment of inertia depends on the shape, mass distribution, 
      and axis of rotation of the object. It is a rotational analog of a mass for 
      linear motion.  For a point mass the moment of inertia is just the product of
       mass and the square of perpendicular distance to the rotation axis. 
       If a point object has a mass <m>m</m> and is rotating about an  axis 
       then its moment of inertia, <m>I</m> is given by <m>I=mr^{2}.</m> 
       where <m>r</m> is a distance  of the object from the axis of rotation [figure <xref ref="micont1a"/>]. 
       If there are an infinite number of point objects each at a distance <m>r_{i}</m> are 
       rotating about an axis, then the moment of inertia (M.I) of these discrete 
       objects are given as 
      </p>
    <figure>
      <caption></caption>
      <sidebyside widths="30% 30% 30%">
        <figure xml:id="micont1a">
          <caption></caption>
          <image source="micont1a.png"/>
      </figure>
          <figure xml:id="micont1b">
              <caption></caption>
              <image source="micont1b.png"/>
          </figure>
          <figure xml:id="micont1c">
              <caption></caption>
              <image source="micont1c.png"/>
          </figure>
         </sidebyside>
  </figure>
<p>
  <me>
    I=\sum\limits_{i=1}^{n} m_{i}r^{2}_{i} = m_{1} r^{2}_{1} + m_{2} r_{2}^{2}+\cdots ,
   </me>
   as shown in figure <xref ref="micont1b"/>. An extended object consists of a 
   continuous distribution of mass at a continually varying distance from 
   the axis of rotation, its moment of inertia can be written as, 
   <me>
    I=\int\,dI=\int\limits_{0}^{M} r^{2}\,dm 
   </me>
   where <m>\,dm</m> is a differential (infinitely small) mass of the object 
   [figure <xref ref="micont1c"/>] and <m>r</m> is a distance of this differential 
   mass from axis of rotation.
</p>
   </introduction>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-paral_axis">
  <title>Parallel axis theorem</title>
  <p>
    The moment of inertia of a body depends upon the axis of rotation and there are 
    many axes possible about which a body can rotate. Hence the parallel axis 
    theorem provides a relationship between the moment of inertia of a body 
    about an axis passing through its center of mass to any other axis of a body 
    which is parallel to the axis through center of mass.
  </p> 
  <figure xml:id="miparallel1">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="miparallel1.png" width="30%"/>
</figure>
  <p>
    Consider an elementary mass <m>m_{i}</m> at a distance <m>r_{i}</m> 
    from the center of mass of a body and at a distance <m>r</m> from the 
    axis of rotation through a point p [figure <xref ref="miparallel1"/>], then the moment of 
    inertia of that point mass is given by 
    <me>
      I=\sum_{i} m_{i}r^{2} = \sum_{i} m_{i}\left(d+r_{i}\right)^{2}
    </me>
    <me>
      =\sum_{i} m_{i}\left(\vec{d}+\vec{r}_{i}\right)\cdot \left(\vec{d}+\vec{r}_{i}\right)
    </me>
    <me>
      =\sum_{i} m_{i}r^{2}_{i}+d^{2}\sum_{i} m_{i}+2\vec{d}\cdot\sum_{i} m_{i}r_{i}
    </me>
    In this expression <m>\sum_{i} m_{i}r^{2}_{i}=I_{cm},</m> a moment of inertia of 
    the body about an axis through center of mass, <m>\sum_{i} m_{i} =M</m>, the mass of a body, 
       <m>I</m>, moment of inertia of a body about an  axis parallel to the axis through 
       the center of mass, <m>d,</m> a distance between parallel axes, and 
       <me>
        \sum_{i} m_{i}r_{i}=\left(\frac{\sum_{i} m_{i}r_{i}}{M} \right)M \rightarrow 0.
       </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Since the position of the center of mass lies at origin (0,0), i.e., <m>r_{i}=0. </m>
          <me>
            \therefore  \quad I  =  I_{cm} + M d^{2} 
          </me>
          The  <term>parallel axis theorem</term> states that the moment of inertia 
          of a body about an axis parallel to an axis passing through the center of mass 
          is equal to the sum of the moment of inertia of body about an axis passing 
          through center of mass and product of mass and square of the distance between the two axes.
        </p>
</subsection>


<subsection xml:id="subsec-perpend_axis">
  <title>Perpendicular axis theorem</title>
  <figure xml:id="miperp1">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="miperp1.png" width="30%"/>
</figure>
  <p>
    The <term>perpendicular axis theorem</term> states that the moment of inertia of a 
    planar body (plane lamina) about an axis perpendicular to its plane is equal 
    to the sum of its moments of inertia about two other perpendicular axes lying 
    in the plane of the body.
<me>
  I_{z}=I_{x}+I_{y}
</me>
  </p>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-mi_ring">
  <title>Moment of Inertia of a Ring or Hoop</title>
  <introduction>

  <figure>
    <caption></caption>
    <sidebyside widths="25% 30% 35%">
      <figure xml:id="miring1">
        <caption></caption>
        <image source="miring1.png"/>
    </figure>
        <figure xml:id="miring2">
            <caption></caption>
            <image source="miring2.png"/>
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="miring3">
            <caption></caption>
            <image source="miring3.png"/>
        </figure>
         </sidebyside>
</figure>
 
  <p>
    As moment inertia depends upon the shape, mass distribution, and position of axis of rotation. 
    Here are some conditions discussed below for a ring.
  </p>
</introduction>
 
<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-miring_cm">
  <title>About an axis passing through its center of mass and perpendicular to its plane</title>
  <p>
    Consider a small element of mass <m>\,dm </m> of a rim of the ring of radius 
   <m>r</m> is rotating about an axis passing passing through its center of 
   mass and perpendicular to its plane [figure <xref ref="miring1"/>], 
   then the moment of inertia of that elemental mass is given by
   <me>
    \,dI=\,dm r^{2}.
   </me>
       Therefore moment of inertia of a whole ring about that axis is 
       <me>
        I=\int\,dI=\int\limits_{0}^{M}\,dm r^{2} = r^{2}\left.m\right|_{0}^{M}= Mr^{2} = I_{cm}
       </me>
           where <m>M</m> is the mass of the ring. 
  </p>
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-miring_rim">
  <title>About an axis passing through its rim and perpendicular to its plane</title>
  <p>
    Consider a ring of mass <m>M</m> and radius <m>r</m>  is rotating about an 
    axis passing passing through its rim and perpendicular to its plane 
    [figure <xref ref="miring2"/>], then the moment of inertia of that ring can be obtained by
    <me>
      I_{rim}=I_{cm}+Md^{2} = Mr^{2}+Mr^{2} =2Mr^{2}
    </me>
  </p>
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-miring_diam">
  <title>About an axis through its diameter</title>
  <p>
    The moment of inertia of a ring about its center of mass and 
    perpendicular to its plane [figure <xref ref="miring3"/>], is 
    <me>
      I_{cm}=Mr^{2}.
    </me>
    Now using the perpendicular axis theorem, we have 
    <me>
      I_{z}=I_{x}+I_{y} =2I_{x}.
    </me>
    As ring is a symmetrical object <m>I_{x}</m> is considered as equal to <m>I_{y}</m>. Hence 
    <me>
      I_{cm}=I_{z}=Mr^{2}=2I_{x}
    </me>
    <me>
      \therefore\quad I_{x}= I_{y}=I_{diameter}=\frac{1}{2}Mr^{2}
    </me>
     </p>
</subsubsection>
</subsection>


<subsection xml:id="subsec-mi_rod">
  <title>Moment of Inertia of a Rod</title>
  <introduction>

  <figure>
    <caption></caption>
    <sidebyside widths="30% 30%">
      <figure xml:id="mirod2">
        <caption></caption>
        <image source="mirod2.png"/>
    </figure>
        <figure xml:id="mirod1">
            <caption></caption>
            <image source="mirod1.png"/>
        </figure>
         </sidebyside>
</figure>
     </introduction>
 

     <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-mirod_cm">
      <title>About an axis passing through its center of mass and perpendicular to its plane</title>
      <p>
        The moment of inertia of a rod of length <m>L</m> and mass <m>M</m> about 
        an axis passing through its center of mass [figure <xref ref="mirod2"/>] 
        can be find by considering an elementary mass <m>\,dm </m> of a rod of 
        infinitesimal thickness <m>\,dx</m> at a distance <m>x</m> from the 
        axis of rotation, then the moment of inertia of this elementary mass (strip) is given by
        <me>
          \,dI = \,dm x^{2}
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{or,}\quad I = \int \,dI = \int\limits_{-\frac{L}{2}}^{\frac{L}{2}}\left(\frac{M}{L}\,dx\right)x^{2}
        </me>
        <me>
          \because \quad \,dm = \left(\frac{M}{L}\,dx\right)
        </me>
        <me>
          i.e., \text{mass of a strip} =(\text{mass per unit length of a rod})\cdot (\text{length of a strip})
        </me>
        <me>
          \therefore\quad I =\frac{M}{L} \int\limits_{-\frac{L}{2}}^{\frac{L}{2}} x^{2} \,dx
        </me>
        <me>
          = \frac{M}{L}\left(\frac{x^{3}}{3}\right)_{-\frac{L}{2}}^{\frac{L}{2}}
        </me>
        <me>
          = \frac{M}{3L}\left[\left(\frac{L}{2}\right)^{3}-\left(-\frac{L}{2}\right)^{3}\right]
        </me>
        <me>
          =\frac{2M}{3L}\left(\frac{L^{3}}{8}\right)=\frac{1}{12}ML^{2}
        </me>
          </p>
     </subsubsection>

     <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-mirod_edge">
      <title>About an axis passing through its one edge and perpendicular to its plane</title>
      <p>
        Consider a rod of length <m>L</m> and mass <m>M</m> is rotating about an axis 
        passing through one of its edges as shown in figure <xref ref="mirod1"/>. 
        To find the moment of inertia of such a rod consider an elementary mass 
        <m>\,dm </m> of a rod of infinitesimal thickness <m>\,dx</m> at a distance 
        <m>x</m> from the axis of rotation, then the moment of inertia of this elementary mass is given by
        <me>
          \,dI = \,dm x^{2}
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{or,}\quad I = \int \,dI = \int\limits_{0}^{L}\left(\frac{M}{L}\,dx\right)x^{2}
        </me>
        <me>
          \therefore\quad I =\frac{M}{L}\int\limits_{0}^{L} x^{2} \,dx
        </me>
        <me>
          = \frac{M}{L}\left(\frac{x^{3}}{3}\right)_{0}^{L}
        </me>
        <me>
          = \frac{M}{3L}(L^{3}-0)=\frac{1}{3}ML^{2}
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
       <alert>Alternative</alert> Using parallel axis theorem, 
       <me>
        I_{edge} = I_{cm}+Md^{2}
       </me>
       <me>
        =\frac{1}{12}ML^{2} +M\left(\frac{L}{2}\right)^{2}=\frac{1}{3}ML^{2}
       </me>
           here, <m>d</m> is the distance between axis of rotation and an axis through center of mass of a rod.
      </p>
     </subsubsection>

     <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-mirod_length">
      <title>About an axis passing along its length and through the center of mass</title>
      <p>
        If the rod is negligibly thin (slender rod), then <m>I_{z}=0</m>, 
        otherwise depends upon of its shape, its moment of inertia can be obtained 
        similar to that for a solid cylinder 
        <me>
          I=\frac{1}{2}mr^{2}
        </me>
       or as for a rectangular prism 
       <me>
        I_{z}=\frac{1}{12}m(x^{2}+y^{2})
       </me>
       </p>
     </subsubsection>
</subsection>


<subsection xml:id="subsec-mi_disk">
  <title>Moment of Inertia of a Disk</title>
  <introduction>
   
  <figure>
    <caption></caption>
    <sidebyside widths="30% 30% 30%">
      <figure xml:id="midisk1">
        <caption></caption>
        <image source="midisk1.png"/>
    </figure>
        <figure xml:id="midisk2">
            <caption></caption>
            <image source="midisk2.png"/>
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="midisk3">
          <caption></caption>
          <image source="midisk3.png"/>
      </figure>
         </sidebyside>
</figure> 
  </introduction>

  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-midisk_cm">
    <title>About an axis passing through its center of mass and perpendicular to its plane</title>
    <p>
      Consider a disk of radius <m>R</m> and mass <m>M</m> is rotating about an axis 
      passing through its center of mass and perpendicular to its plane [figure <xref ref="midisk1"/>]. 
      To find the moment of inertia of such a disk consider an elementary ring of radius 
      <m>r</m>, thickness <m>\,dx</m>, and mass <m>\,dm</m> then the moment of inertia 
      of this elementary ring (annulus) is given by
      <me>
        \,dI = \,dm r^{2}
      </me>
      <me>
        \text{or,}\quad I = \int \,dI = \int\limits_{0}^{R}\left(\frac{M}{\pi R^{2}}(2\pi r\,dr)\right)r^{2} 
      </me>
      <me>
        \because \text{mass of a ring} =(\text{mass per unit area of a disk})\cdot (\text{area of a ring})
      </me>
      <me>
        \text{or,}\quad I = \frac{2M}{R^{2}}\int\limits_{0}^{R}\left(r^{3}\,dr\right) 
      </me>
      <me>
        =\frac{2M}{R^{2}}\left.\frac{r^{4}}{4}\right\vert_{0}^{R} 
      </me>
      <me>
        =\frac{M}{2R^{2}}(R^{4}-0)=\frac{1}{2}MR^{2}
      </me>
       </p>
  </subsubsection>

  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-midisk_diam">
    <title>About an axis through its diameter</title>
    <p>
      Using perpendicular axis theorem, [figure <xref ref="midisk2"/>] 
      <me>
        I_{z}=I_{x}+I_{y}
      </me>
      <me>
        \text{But}\quad I_{z}=I_{cm}=\frac{1}{2}MR^{2}
      </me>
      and by symmetry, <me>
        I_{x}=I_{y}
      </me>
            <me>
        \therefore\quad I_{z}=2I_{x} \Rightarrow\quad  I_{x}=\frac{I_{z}}{2}= \frac{1}{4}MR^{2}
      </me>
         </p>
  </subsubsection>

  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-midisk_edge">
    <title>About an axis passing through its edge and perpendicular to its plane</title>
    <p>
      Using parallel axis theorem, [figure <xref ref="midisk3"/>] 
      <me>
        I_{edge}=I_{cm}+Md^{2}=\frac{1}{2}MR^{2} +MR^{2}= \frac{3}{2}MR^{2}
      </me>
          </p>
  </subsubsection>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-mi_plate">
  <title>Moment of Inertia of a Plate</title>
  <introduction>
   <p>

   </p>
  </introduction>

<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-miplate_cmlength">
  <title>About an axis <m>I_{x}</m> passing through its center of mass and parallel to its plane</title>
  <figure xml:id="miplate2">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="miplate2.png" width="30%"/>
</figure>
  <p>
    Consider a plate of length <m>a</m> and width <m>b</m> is made out off 
    number of elementary rods of thickness <m>\,dx</m>, then moment of 
    inertia of that rod about x-axis is given by 
<me>
  I_{x} = \int x^{2}\,dm = \int\limits_{0}^{a}\frac{1}{12}\,dmb^{2}
</me>
here <m>\,dm</m> = (mass per unit area)(area of a rod), by considering neglible plate thickness.
<me>
  \therefore \quad I_{x} = \frac{1}{12}b^{2}\int\limits_{0}^{a}\frac{M}{ab}b\,dx 
</me>
<me>
  = \frac{Mb^{2}}{12a}\left.x\right|_{0}^{a} =  \frac{1}{12}Mb^{2}
</me>
  </p>
</subsubsection>


<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-miplate_cmwide">
  <title>About an axis <m>I_{y} </m> passing through its center of mass and parallel to its plane</title>

  <figure xml:id="miplate3">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="miplate3.png" width="30%"/>
</figure>

  <p>
    Consider a plate of length <m>a</m> and width <m>b</m> is made out off number of 
    elementary rods of thickness <m>\,dy</m>, then moment of inertia of that rod about y-axis is given by 
    <me>
      I_{y} = \int y^{2}\,dm = \int\limits_{0}^{b}\frac{1}{12}\,dma^{2}
    </me>
    <m>\,dm</m>  = (mass per unit area)(area of a rod), by considering neglible plate thickness.
    <me>
      \therefore \quad I_{y} = \frac{1}{12}a^{2}\int\limits_{0}^{b}\frac{M}{ab}a\,dy =  \frac{1}{12}Ma^{2}
    </me>
      </p>
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-miplate_perpnd">
  <title>About an axis passing through its center of mass and perpendicular to its plane</title>
  <figure xml:id="miplate1">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="miplate1.png" width="30%"/>
</figure>
  <p>
    Consider a plate of length <m>a</m> and width <m>b</m> is made out off number 
    of elementary rods of thickness <m>\,dx</m>, then moment of inertia of that rod about z-axis is given by 
    <me>
      \,dI_{z} = \left[\,dI_{cm}+\,dm \,x^{2}\right]\quad [\text{parallel axis theorem}]
    </me>
    <me>
      \text{or,}\quad \,dI_{z} = \left[\frac{1}{12}\,dm\,b^{2}+\,dm \,x^{2}\right]
    </me>
    <me>
      \text{or,}\quad \,dI_{z} = \left[\frac{1}{12}\left(\frac{M}{ab}b\,dx\right)\,b^{2}+\left(\frac{M}{ab}b\,dx\right) \,x^{2}\right]
    </me>
    <me>
      \,dm = \text{(mass per unit area)}(\text{area of a rod})
    </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      Hence the moment of inertia of a plate about center of mass is given by
      <me>
        I_{z}=\int\,dI_{z} = \frac{M}{a}\int\limits_{-\frac{a}{2}}^{\frac{a}{2}}\left[\frac{1}{12}b^{2}\,dx +x^{2}\,dx \right]
      </me>
      <me>
        = \frac{M}{a}\left[\frac{1}{12}b^{2}\left.x\right\vert_{-\frac{a}{2}}^{\frac{a}{2}} +\left.\frac{x^{3}}{3}\right\vert_{-\frac{a}{2}}^{\frac{a}{2}} \right] 
      </me>
      <me>
        I_{z} =\frac{M}{a}\left[\frac{1}{12}b^{2}\left(\frac{a}{2}+\frac{a}{2}\right)+\frac{1}{3}\left(\frac{a^{3}}{8}+ \frac{a^{3}}{8}\right)\right]
      </me>
      <me>
        =\frac{M}{12}\left[a^{2}+b^{2}\right]
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
        <alert>Alternative:</alert> Moment of inertia of plate about <m>I_{z}</m> 
        using perpendicular axis theorem,
        <me>
          I_{z}=I_{x}+I_{y} = \frac{1}{12}Mb^{2}+\frac{1}{12}Ma^{2}
        </me>
        <me>
          =\frac{M}{12}\left(a^{2}+b^{2}\right)
        </me>
      </p>
</subsubsection>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-mi_cylnd">
  <title>Moment of Inertia of a Cylinder</title>
  <introduction>
   
  <figure>
    <caption></caption>
    <sidebyside widths="25% 25% 25%">
      <figure xml:id="mihcyl1">
        <caption></caption>
        <image source="mihcyl1.png"/>
    </figure>
        <figure xml:id="mithcyl1">
            <caption></caption>
            <image source="mithcyl1.png"/>
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="miscyl1">
          <caption></caption>
          <image source="miscyl1.png"/>
      </figure>
         </sidebyside>
</figure> 
  </introduction>

  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-micyl_cm">
    <title>Moment of inertia of a thin hollow cylinder about an axis passing through its center of mass and perpendicular to its plane</title>
    <p>
      Consider an elemental ring  of thickness <m>\,dx</m> at a distance 
      <m>x</m> from the center of mass of a hollow cylinder [Figure <xref ref="mihcyl1"/>], 
      then the moment of inertia of this ring is given by 
      <me>
        \,dI=\,dm\,R^{2}
      </me>
      <me>
        \therefore\quad I = \int\limits_{0}^{l}\left(\frac{M}{2\pi Rl}\right)(2\pi R \,dx)R^{2}=\frac{MR^{2}}{l}\left(l\right)_{0}^{l}=MR^{2}
      </me>
       [Mass of an elemental ring = (mass per unit area of a cylinder) (area of a ring).]
  Here <m>M</m> is mass of the cylinder, <m>R</m> is its radius,  and <m>l</m> is its length.
    </p>
  </subsubsection> 

  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-micyl_percm">
    <title>Moment of inertia of a thick hollow cylinder about an axis passing through its center of mass and perpendicular to its plane</title>
    <p>
      Consider an elemental thin cylinder of length <m>l</m>,  
      thickness <m>\,dr</m> at a distance <m>r</m> from the center of 
      mass of a thick hollow cylinder of outer radius <m>R_{2}</m> and inner radius 
      <m>R_{1}</m> [Figure <xref ref="mithcyl1"/>], then the moment of inertia of this cylinder is given by 
      <me>
        \,dI=\,dm\,r^{2} = \left[\frac{M}{\pi\left(R^{2}_{2}-R^{2}_{1}\right)l}\right]\left(2\pi r\,dr l\right)r^{2}
      </me>
      <me>
        \text{or,}\quad I = \left(\frac{2M}{R_{2}^{2}-R_{1}^{2}}\right) \int\limits_{R_{1}}^{R_{2}}r^{3}\,dr
      </me>
      <me>
        =\left(\frac{2M}{R_{2}^{2}-R_{1}^{2}}\right)\left(\frac{r^{4}}{4}\right)_{R_{1}}^{R_{2}}
      </me>
      <me>
        \therefore\quad I = \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{M}{R_{2}^{2}-R_{1}^{2}}\right)\left(R_{2}^{4}-R_{1}^{4}\right) 
      </me>
      <me>
        = \frac{1}{2}M\left(R_{2}^{2}+R_{1}^{2}\right)
      </me>
     [Mass of an elemental cylinder = (mass per unit volume of a thick cylinder) (volume of elemental cylinder).]
    </p>
  </subsubsection>

  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-micyl_cmsolid">
    <title>Moment of inertia of a solid cylinder about an axis passing through its center of mass and perpendicular to its plane</title>
    <p>
      Consider a concentric cylindrical shell of length <m>l</m>, radius <m>r</m>, 
      and thickness <m>\,dr</m> in a solid cylinder of mass <m>M</m> and  
      radius <m>R</m> [Figure <xref ref="miscyl1"/>], then the moment of inertia of the shell is given by 
      <me>
        \,dI_{z}=\,dm\,r^{2} = \left[\frac{M}{\pi R^{2}l}\right]\left(2\pi r\,dr l\right)r^{2}
      </me>
      <me>
        \text{or,}\quad I_{z} = \frac{2M}{R^{2}} \int\limits_{0}^{R}r^{3}\,dr
      </me>
      <me>
        =\frac{2M}{R^{2}}\left(\frac{r^{4}}{4}\right)_{0}^{R}
      </me>
      <me>
        \therefore\quad I_{z} = \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{M}{R^{2}}\right)\left(R^{4}-0\right) = \frac{1}{2}MR^{2}
      </me>
      Show that moment of inertia of a solid cylinder about 
      <me>
        I_{x} =I_{y} = \frac{M}{12}\left(3R^{2}+l^{2}\right).
      </me>
       </p>
  </subsubsection>
</subsection>


<subsection xml:id="subsec-mi_cone">
  <title>Moment of Inertia of a Cone</title>
  <introduction>
    
  <figure>
